<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2012-03-01T08:15:45-07:00</updated>
<published>2012-03-01T08:15:45-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8666&amp;p=90765#p90765</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8666&amp;p=90765#p90765"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Why do you personally homebrew?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8666&amp;p=90765#p90765"><![CDATA[
A long time ago, I was writing simple puzzle games for the Apple II in BASIC with assembly language subroutines. (The NES's CPU uses the same instruction set as the Apple II's CPU.)<br /><br />Fast forward to years later when I was CHR-hacking SMB1 to replace Mario with different characters. Then I tried to hack Contra but discovered that its graphics were compressed, so instead I decided to try to write my own platformer. Obviously, other things intervened, and the puzzle games I wrote to familiarize myself with the platform ended up taking over.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu Mar 01, 2012 8:15 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
